english:
  title: Viewing the Sea Waves on the Road to Heunghaeto and Songnado
  author: Park Hyo-su
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A violent wind suddenly rises and overturns the azure deep.
    Heaven and water merge as darkness swallows all.
    Silver mountains—ten thousand petals—dip and rise again,
    While a hundred thunderous drums beat out in unison.

    Fusan seems to drift away, the earth's axis shakes.
    The Dragon King sits anxious, his palace totters.
    Wave sprites scatter wildly, aquatic creatures flee in confusion—
    Who stirs this chaos? The great kun and the mighty whale.

    If only I could draw my sword that props up heaven,
    And with one sweep brush away the scales like falling snow!
    Then let the Eastern Sea be cleansed to smoothness of silk,
    Reflecting again the sun's clear and brilliant light.

    Jaos and dragons, shrimp and crabs would find their peace,
    Disporting themselves in sacred benediction's cool, gentle streams.
  footnotes:
    - 'Fusan (扶桑): a mythological tree marking the easternmost edge of the world in classical Chinese cosmology'
    - The 'sword that props up heaven' (倚天劒) is a legendary blade from Chinese mythology, symbolizing the power to restore cosmic order
    - The poem moves from depicting chaotic natural forces to a vision of restored harmony through virtuous intervention
